%N A396255 Irregular table read by rows: let p = prime(n) and d be the k-th divisor of p-1. Then T(n,k) is the algebraic degree of tau(chi) over Q, where chi is any Dirichlet character modulo p of order d, and tau is the Gauss sum.
%C A396255 If chi has order d, then Q(tau(chi)) is the compositum of Q(zeta_d) and Q(zeta_p)^G, where G is the unique index-d subgroup of (Z/pZ)*. See the Math Stack Exchange link below.
%H A396255 Jianing Song, <a href="/A396255/b396255.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10001</a> (Rows 1..713)
%H A396255 Math Stack Exchange, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/5137599/let-chi-be-a-nontrivial-dirichlet-charcater-of-order-d-modulo-p-is-it-tr">Let chi be a nontrivial Dirichlet charcater of order d modulo p. Is it true that zeta_d is in Q(tau(chi))?</a>.
%F A396255 T(n,k) = d*EulerPhi(d), where d is the k-th divisor of prime(n)-1.
%e A396255 The first rows:
%e A396255   1;
%e A396255   1, 2;
%e A396255   1, 2, 8;
%e A396255   1, 2, 6, 12;
%e A396255   1, 2, 20, 40;
%e A396255   1, 2, 6, 8, 12, 48;
%e A396255   1, 2, 8, 32, 128;
%e A396255   1, 2, 6, 12, 54, 108;
%e A396255   1, 2, 110, 220;
%e A396255   1, 2, 8, 42, 84, 336.
%e A396255 See A396254 for explanations of rows 3 and 4.
%o A396255 (PARI) row(n) = my(p=prime(n), v=divisors(p-1), len=#v); for(i=1, len, v[i]=v[i]*eulerphi(v[i])); v
%Y A396255 Cf. A008328 (row lengths), A002618 ({d*EulerPhi(d)}), A104039 (rightmost values of rows).
%Y A396255 Cf. A396254 (another version).
%K A396255 nonn,tabf,easy
%O A396255 1,3
%A A396255 _Jianing Song_, May 20 2026
